44||1||12||0||1||0||47||0||204||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]||[[2006\u201307 La Liga|2006\u201307]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[La Liga]]||23||0||2||0||1||0||4||0||30||0\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 La Liga|2007\u201308]]||18||0||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||0||28||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!41||0||6||0||1||0||10||0||58||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!504||10||57||1||9||1||113||1||683||13\n|}\n\n<span id=\"notes gs1\"></span><sup>1</sup><small>Includes one [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] Serie A play-off match ([[1999\u20132000 Serie A#UEFA Champions League qualification|2000]]).</small>\n\n===International===\n[[File:Thuram et Djorkaeff lors du jubil\u00e9 Pauleta.jpg|thumb|right|Thuram ''(left)'' with compatriot [[Youri Djorkaeff]] in 2009. Both featured in the France squads at the [[FIFA World Cup]]s of [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]] and [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002]], and [[UEFA European Championships]] in [[UEFA Euro 1996|1996]] and [[UEFA Euro 2000|2000]].]]\n\n:Source:<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/thuram-intl.html \"Lilian Thuram \u2013 Century of International Appearances\"]. ''[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]''. Retrieved 30 June 2012.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[France national football team|France national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1994||1||0\n|-\n|1995||5||0\n|-\n|1996||13||0\n|-\n|1997||8||0\n|-\n|1998||16||2\n|-\n|1999||9||0\n|-\n|2000||14||0\n|-\n|2001||4||0\n|-\n|2002||12||0\n|-\n|2003||12||0\n|-\n|2004||9||0\n|-\n|2005||7||0\n|-\n|2006||16||0\n|-\n|2007||10||0\n|-\n|2008||6||0\n|-\n!Total||142||2\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || rowspan=\"2\" | 8 July 1998 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Stade de France]], Saint-Denis || rowspan=\"2\" | {{fb|Croatia}} || 1\u20131 || rowspan=\"2\" | 2\u20131 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]\n|-\n| 2. || 2\u20131\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Monaco'''<ref name=SW>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/lilian-thuram/542/|title=L. Thuram|work=Soccerway|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Coupe de France]]: [[1990\u201391 Coupe de France|1990\u201391]]\n\n'''Parma'''<ref name=SW/>\n*[[Coppa Italia]]: [[1998\u201399 Coppa Italia|1998\u201399]]\n*[[UEFA Cup]]: [[1998\u201399 UEFA Cup|1998\u201399]]\n*[[Supercoppa Italiana]]: [[1999 Supercoppa Italiana|1999]]\n\n'''Juventus'''<ref name=SW/>\n*[[Serie A]]: [[2001\u201302 Serie A|2001\u201302]], [[2002\u201303 Serie A|2002\u201303]]\n*Supercoppa Italiana: [[2002 Supercoppa Italiana|2002]], [[2003 Supercoppa Italiana|2003]]\n\n'''Barcelona'''<ref name=SW/>\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]: [[2006 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2006]]\n\n'''France'''<ref name=SW/>\n*[[FIFA World Cup]]: [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]]\n*[[UEFA European Championship]]: [[UEFA Euro 2000|2000]]\n*[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]: [[2003 FIFA Confederations Cup|2003]]\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[France Football#French Player of the Year|French Player of the Year]]: 1997<ref name=\"France \u2013 Footballer of the Year\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/franpoy.html |title=France \u2013 Footballer of the Year |publisher=RSSSF |date=8 January 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905115225/http://rsssf.com/miscellaneous/franpoy.html |archivedate= 5 September 2015 }}</ref>\n*[[Guerin d'Oro]]: 1997<ref name=\"Guerin d'Oro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/italpoy.html |title=Italy \u2013 Footballer of the Year |publisher=RSSSF |accessdate=6 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121013030/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/italpoy.html |archivedate=21 January 2015 }}</ref>\n*[[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|FIFA World Cup Bronze Ball]]: 1998<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/fifa-gb98.html|title=FIFA Awards - World Cup 1998 \"Golden Ball\"|publisher=RSSSF|author1=Jos\u00e9 Luis Pierrend|date=9 June 1999|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[FIFA World Cup All-Star Team]]: 1998, 2006<ref name=\"MasterCard All-Star Team of the 1998 World Cup\"/>\n*[[European Sports Media#ESM Team of the Year|ESM Team of the Year]]: 1998\u201399, 2002\u201303<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/esm-xi.html|title=ESM XI|publisher=RSSSF|author1=Karel Stokkermans|date=14 March 2007|accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA European Championship Teams of the Tournament|UEFA Euro Team of the Tournament]]: 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/finals/history/memories/newsid=1627525.html|title=UEFA Euro 2000 team of the tournament|website=uefa.com|publisher=UEFA|date=1 January 2011|accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref>\n*[[FIFA 100]]: 2004<ref name=\"Pele\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/3533891.stm |title=Pele's list of the greatest |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 March 2004 |accessdate=15 June 2013 }}</ref>\n*[[FIFPro World XI]]: 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fifpro.org/en/award-history/fifpro-world-xi-2005-2006|title=FIFPro World XI 2005/2006|publisher=FIFPro|date=20 December 2013|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Troph\u00e9e d'honneur UNFP]]: 2009\n*[[\u00c9quipe type sp\u00e9ciale 20 ans des troph\u00e9es UNFP]]: 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfp.fr/corporate/article/eden-hazard-meilleur-joueur-de-ligue-1.htm|title=Eden Hazard meilleur joueur de Ligue 1|trans-title=Eden Hazard best Ligue 1 player|publisher=LFP|language=French|date=22 May 2011|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''Orders'''\n*[[Chevalier of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]: 1998<ref name=Legion/>\n*[[Officier of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]: 2013<ref>{{cite journal |date=31 March 2013 |title=D\u00e9cret du 29 mars 2013 portant promotion et nomination |trans-title=Decree of 29 March 2013 on promotion and appointment |url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000027248227 |journal=Journal Officiel de la R\u00e9publique Fran\u00e7aise |volume=2013 |issue=0077 |page=5480 |id=PREX1307219D |accessdate=24 August 2019 |language=French}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{FIFA}}\n* {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120731025721/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/futbol/temporada_07-08/plantilla/jugadors/thuram.html |title=FC Barcelona player profile}}\n* {{LFP Ligue 1|lilian-thuram}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = France squads\n| bg = #002395\n| fg = white\n| bordercolor = #ED2939\n| list1 = \n{{France squad UEFA Euro 1996}}\n{{France squad 1998 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{France squad UEFA Euro 2000}}\n{{France squad 2002 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{France squad 2003 FIFA Confederations Cup}}\n{{France squad UEFA Euro 2004}}\n{{France squad 2006 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{France squad UEFA Euro 2008}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{FIFA 100}}\n{{French Player of the Year}}\n{{1998 FIFA World Cup Team of the Tournament}}\n{{UEFA Euro 2000 Team of the Tournament}}\n{{2006 FIFA World Cup Team of the Tournament}}\n{{FIFA World Cup Bronze Ball}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thuram, Lilian}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Thuram family]]\n[[Category:French people of Guadeloupean descent]]\n[[Category:Black French sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Guadeloupean footballers]]\n[[Category:French footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:AS Monaco FC players]]\n[[Category:Parma Calcio 1913 players]]\n[[Category:Juventus F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n[[Category:France under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:France international footballers]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1993 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1996 players]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2000 players]]\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2003 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2004 players]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2008 players]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games bronze medalists for France]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:UEFA European Championship-winning players]]\n[[Category:FIFA Confederations Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:FIFA Century Club]]\n[[Category:FIFA 100]]\n[[Category:French expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Monaco]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Monaco]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Anti-racism activists]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Lilian Thuram\n| image = Lilian_Thuram_-_F\u00e9vrier_2013.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Thuram in 2013\n| fullname = Ruddy Lilian Thuram-Ulien<ref name=Legion>{{cite journal |date=25 July 1998 |title=D\u00e9cret du 24 juillet 1998 portant nomination \u00e0 titre exceptionnel |trans-title=Decree of 24 July 1998 appointing on an exceptional basis |url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000374701 |journal=Journal Officiel de la R\u00e9publique Fran\u00e7aise |volume=1998 |issue=170 |page=11376 |id=PREX9801916D |accessdate=24 August 2019 |language=French}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1972|01|01|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifadata.com/document/fwc/2006/PDF/FWC_2006_SquadLists.pdf |title=2006 FIFA World Cup Germany: List of players: France |publisher=FIFA |page=11 |date=21 March 2014 |accessdate=3 September 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Pointe-\u00e0-Pitre]], Guadeloupe\n| height = 1.82 m<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arxiu.fcbarcelona.cat/web/castellano/futbol/temporada_07-08/plantilla/jugadors/thuram.html |title=Lilian Thuram |publisher=FC Barcelona |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| years1 = 1991\u20131996\n| clubs1 = [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]\n| caps1 = 155\n| goals1 = 8\n| years2 = 1996\u20132001\n| clubs2 = [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]]\n| caps2 = 163\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2001\u20132006\n| clubs3 = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]\n| caps3 = 144\n| goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2006\u20132008\n| clubs4 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| caps4 = 41\n| goals4 = 0\n| totalcaps = 503\n| totalgoals = 10\n| nationalyears1 = 1994\u20132008\n| nationalteam1 = [[France national football team|France]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 142\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| medaltemplates = {{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{fb|FRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 France]]|}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 Germany]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[UEFA Euro 2000|2000 Belgium-Netherlands]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2003 FIFA Confederations Cup|2003 France]]|}}\n}}\n'''Ruddy Lilian Thuram-Ulien''' ({{IPA-fr|li.lj\u0251\u0303 ty.\u0281am}};<ref>{{cite AV media | people =Lilian Thuram | year =2012 | title =Lilian Thuram, Vid\u00e9o de soutien pour l'\u00e9galit\u00e9 des droits | medium =YouTube | language =French | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VsPzvMebsT0 | accessdate =28 January 2012 | time = 0:01 | publisher = Projet Entourage | quote =Bonjour, je m'appelle Lilian Thuram.}}</ref> born 1 January 1972) is a French retired professional [[association football|football]] [[defender (association football)|defender]] and the most [[cap (sport)|capped]] player in the history of the [[France national football team|France national team]] with 142 appearances between 1994 and 2008.\n\nThuram played at the top flight in France,Italy and Spain for over 15 seasons, including ten in [[Serie A]] with both [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] and [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]. With France, Thuram was a key player for the team that won the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], his side also won [[UEFA Euro 2000]], and was in the runner-up squad for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]]. A quick, powerful and versatile player, he was capable of playing both as a [[centre-back]] or as a [[Right back (association football)|right-back]], and was competent both offensively and defensively. Despite his physical and aggressive playing style, Thuram has been described as a \"studious\" figure off the pitch;<ref name=\"Euro 2000 Profile: Lilian Thuram\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/france/squad/744708.stm|title=Euro 2000 Profile: Lilian Thuram|publisher=BBC|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> in 2010, he became a [[UNICEF]] ambassador, and has stood out for his initiatives to fight against racism.<ref name=\"Thuram a Treviso contro il razzismo\">{{cite web|url=http://treviso24.tv/news/il-campione-lilian-thuram-treviso-contro-il-razzismo.html|title=Il campione Lilian Thuram a Treviso contro il razzismo|publisher=Treviso 24|language=Italian|accessdate=15 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915231101/http://treviso24.tv/news/il-campione-lilian-thuram-treviso-contro-il-razzismo.html|archivedate=15 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nThuram was born in [[Guadeloupe]] in the [[French West Indies]]. His family relocated to mainland France in 1981.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://frenchfootballweekly.com/2013/09/06/no-thrills-no-attitude-just-thuram/|title=No thrills, No attitude, Just Thuram|date=6 September 2013|accessdate=14 October 2013|work=French Football Weekly}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2013}}\nThuram's football career began with [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] in [[Ligue 1]] in 1991. He then transferred to [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] (1996\u20132001) and then to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] (2001\u20132006) for \u00a325&nbsp;million, and eventually to [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in 2006.\n\n===Monaco===\nThuram started his professional career with [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] in 1991. He only made one appearance that season, but was officially promoted to the first team the following season, when he would go on to make 19 appearances. He was inserted into the starting XI by the end of 1992 and would go on to make 155 league appearances for the [[Ligue 1]] outfit, before transferring to [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] in the summer of 1996. He made his national team debut in 1994, while at Monaco. With Monaco, he most notably won the [[1990\u201391 Coupe de France|Coupe de France in 1991]], also reaching the final of the [[1991\u201392 European Cup Winners' Cup]].\n\n===Parma===\nIn July 1996, Thuram made a high-profile transfer to Italy to join [[Serie A]] club Parma. In his first season, he made over 40 appearances for the club in all competitions, scoring one goal, as Parma finished second in the [[1996\u201397 Serie A]] to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]. He maintained a starting position in defence throughout his time with Parma, making 163 Serie A appearances and scoring one league goal. In all, he made over 200 appearances for the club, really making a name for himself, also earning caps for France. Following another overly impressive season in 2000\u201301, where Parma reached the [[2000\u201301 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia final]], and finishing the [[2000\u201301 Serie A|Serie A]] season in fourth place, Thuram,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/1394566.stm|title=Juve snatch Thuram|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 June 2001|accessdate=6 April 2010}}</ref> along with teammate [[Gianluigi Buffon]], transferred to Juventus. His transfer cost the club 80 billion [[Italian lira|Italian lire]] (\u20ac41,316,552).<ref>Parma AC SpA Report and Accounts on 30 June 2001 {{in lang|it}}</ref> While at Parma, along with eventual Juventus teammates Buffon and [[Fabio Cannavaro]], Thuram won both the [[1998\u201399 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] and the [[1998\u201399 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] during the 1998\u201399 season, immediately followed by the [[1999 Supercoppa Italiana]].\n\n===Juventus===\nIn the summer of 2001, Thuram made a transfer to Juventus, along with goalkeeper Gianluigi Buffon. Thuram formed defensive partnerships with the likes of [[Ciro Ferrara]], [[Paolo Montero]], [[Gianluca Pessotto]], [[Mark Iuliano]], [[Alessandro Birindelli]], [[Igor Tudor]], [[Gianluca Zambrotta]], [[Nicola Legrottaglie]], [[Fabio Cannavaro]], [[Giorgio Chiellini]], [[Federico Balzaretti]] and [[Jonathan Zebina]] during his five-year tenure with the club. In his first season with the club, as a right back under [[Marcello Lippi]], Thuram won the [[2001\u201302 Serie A]] title, also reaching the final of the [[2001\u201302 Coppa Italia]]. Juventus started the following season by winning the [[2002 Supercoppa Italiana]], and defended their [[2002\u201303 Serie A|Serie A title]], also reaching the [[2003 UEFA Champions League Final|UEFA Champions League final]], where they were defeated by rivals [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] on penalties.\n\nJuventus won the [[2003 Supercoppa Italiana]] the following season, reaching another [[2003\u201304 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia final]], but finished in a disappointing 3rd place in [[2003\u201304 Serie A|Serie A]], and failed to progress past the second round in the [[2003\u201304 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]. During the [[2004\u201305 Serie A|2004\u201305]] and [[2005\u201306 Serie A|2005\u201306]] seasons under coach [[Fabio Capello]], Thuram, along with Fabio Cannavaro in the centre of defence, with [[Gianluigi Buffon]] in goal, {{fact span|date=December 2012|text=[[Gianluca Zambrotta]] at left back,}}, and {{fact span|date=December 2012|text=[[Jonathan Zebina]] at right back}} formed one of the most expensive, but also most feared, defences in Europe and Italy. During these next two seasons with the club, Thuram won the ''[[Scudetto]]'' two more times with Juventus, although these consecutive league titles were later revoked due to Juventus' involvement in the [[2006 Italian football scandal]] (''calciopoli''). After five years with Juve, Thuram transferred to [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in the Spanish [[La Liga]], in the wake of the ''calciopoli'' scandal. He managed over 200 total appearances for the club, with two goals.\n\n===Barcelona===\n\n[[Image:Lilian Thuram - 001.jpg|thumb|145px|<center>Thuram with [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in 2008</center>]]\n\nOn 24 July 2006, Thuram signed with Barcelona for \u20ac5&nbsp;million after Juventus were relegated to [[Serie B]] due to the ''calciopoli'' scandal.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120803221330/http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/historic_noticies/futbol/06/Juliol/n06072408.html \"Thuram Signs Contract\"]. ''FCBarcelona.cat''. 24 July 2006. Retrieved 30 June 2012</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20081207072451/http://www.juventus.com/site/filesite/finance/comunicatipricesensitive/21_lug_2006_eng.pdf \"Agreements with the Spanish club FC Barcelona\"] (PDF). Juventus F.C. 21 July 2006. Retrieved 30 June 2012.</ref>\n\nIn Thuram's last season ([[2007\u201308 FC Barcelona season|2007\u201308]]), he was the third- or fourth-choice centre-back after [[Carles Puyol]], [[Gabriel Milito]] and [[Rafael M\u00e1rquez]].<ref name=\"Heart\">{{cite news| title = Thuram move ended by heart defect |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7477866.stm|publisher=BBC Sport| date = 27 June 2008| accessdate =29 June 2007}}</ref> On 26 June 2008, he was reported as having signed a one-year contract with an option for another year with [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]].<ref>{{cite news|url= http://bleacherreport.com/articles/32760-world-football-thuram-signs-with-psg|title=Thuram Signs With PSG|author=Paul Fisher|work=[[Bleacher Report]]|date=26 June 2008|accessdate=12 April 2012}}</ref> The deal, however, was cancelled shortly after because he was diagnosed with a heart defect that had caused the death of his brother.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/7477866.stm|title=Thuram move ended by heart defect|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=12 April 2012|date=27 June 2008}}</ref> On 2 August, he announced his final retirement from professional football due to his condition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=fra/news/newsid=736420.html|title=Thuram retires due to heart condition|publisher=UEFA |date=2 August 2008|accessdate=12 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Italy vs France - FIFA World Cup 2006 final - Lilian Thuram and Zinedine Zidane.jpg|thumb|right|Thuram ''(left)'' alongside [[Zinedine Zidane]], playing for [[France national football team|France]] in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final]].]]\nAfter becoming world champion in 1998, Thuram was an integral part of [[France national football team|France]]'s triumph at [[UEFA Euro 2000]], which led to the team being ranked by [[FIFA]] as number one from 2001\u20132002. He also played in the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]], [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]], [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]] and [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]], in addition to winning the [[2003 FIFA Confederations Cup]].\n\n===1998 World Cup===\nThuram scored only two international goals in his entire career, both of which came in one game \u2013 the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]] semi-final against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]], in which France came back to win 2\u20131 and advance to the [[1998 FIFA World Cup Final|final]]. France defeated [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] 3\u20130 to capture their inaugural [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] and Thuram won the [[Adidas Golden Ball|Bronze Ball]] as the third most valuable player in the tournament. He, [[Bixente Lizarazu]], [[Laurent Blanc]] and [[Marcel Desailly]] formed the backbone of the French defence that conceded only two goals in seven matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/best-players-world-cup-france-98-zidane-ronaldo-thuram-bergkamp-suker |title=Ranked! The 10 best players of France 98 |publisher=FourFourTwo |last1=Wilson |first1=Jonathan |date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===2006 World Cup===\nAfter a brief international retirement, France coach [[Raymond Domenech]] convinced Thuram to return to the French team on 17 August 2005, along with fellow \"[[Golden generation#France (1998\u20132006)|Golden Generation]]\" teammates [[Zinedine Zidane]] and [[Claude Mak\u00e9l\u00e9l\u00e9]], as ''Les Bleus'' struggled to qualify for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]]. Thuram's [[centre back]] partnership with [[William Gallas]] was to be the foundation for France's progression to the final. Thuram earned his 116th cap for France in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group G|group stage match]] against [[Korea Republic national football team|South Korea]] in [[Leipzig]] on 18 June 2006. In that game he equalled Desailly's record number of caps, which he broke in the final group stage match, a 2\u20130 win over [[Togo national football team|Togo]] in [[Cologne]] on 23 June 2006, winning his 117th cap. He was named the [[man of the match]] in France's semi-final 1\u20130 victory against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], coincidentally the same distinction he had earned eight years earlier at the semi-finals of the 1998 World Cup.\n\n===Euro 2008===\nOn 9 June 2008, Thuram took the field against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] in a group match, and became the first player to make 15 [[UEFA European Championship]] finals appearances. The former record of 14 appearances was held by Zinedine Zidane, [[Lu\u00eds Figo]] and [[Karel Poborsk\u00fd]].<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=709189.html \"Thuram sets EURO appearance record\"]. [[UEFA]]. 9 June 2008. Retrieved 30 June 2012.</ref> He played one more game during the tournament, raising the number of his appearances to 16, which record was then equaled a few days later by [[Edwin van der Sar]] from the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] in the quarter-finals. Thuram was the [[captain (association football)|captain]] of France in the tournament. He, along with [[Claude Mak\u00e9l\u00e9l\u00e9]], announced his retirement from international football on 17 June 2008, after France's 2\u20130 loss to [[Italy national football team|Italy]].<ref name=\"retirement\">{{cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/euro2008/story/0,23063,11966_3705170,00.html|title=France duo call it quits|date=18 June 2008|work=[[Sky Sports]]|accessdate=18 June 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/f6gt|archive-date=9 December 2012}}</ref> He finished his career with the national team as France's most capped player with 142 appearances.\n\n==Style of play==\n[[File:Only a game Lilian Thuram (2956628278).jpg|thumb|upright|Thuram's signed Bar\u00e7a shirt, on display at the [[World Museum]] in [[Liverpool]], 2008]]\nThuram was an extremely dominant, consistent, athletic and attentive footballer, who was considered by pundits to be one of the best defenders in the world in his prime.<ref name=\"Euro 2000 Profile: Lilian Thuram\"/><ref name=tuttojuve/> As a defender, he was known for his strength, pace, stamina and his outstanding physical, tactical, and technical attributes, as well as his elegance, ability to read the game, his heavy marking of opponents, and his aggressive tackling, which made him difficult to beat in one on one situations; he also excelled in the air. As a full-back, he was known for his ability to make attacking runs up the flank and contribute to his team's offensive play after winning back the ball.<ref name=tuttojuve>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/gli-eroi-bianconeri/gli-eroi-in-bianconero-lilian-thuram-76208|title=Gli eroi in bianconero: Lilian Thuram|publisher=Tutto Juve|language=Italian|author=Stefano Bedeschi|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"MasterCard All-Star Team of the 1998 World Cup\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/newscentre/news/newsid=71747/index.html|title=MasterCard All-Star Team of the 1998 World Cup|website=fifa.com|publisher=FIFA|date=10 July 1998|accessdate=23 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"From Right to Left\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/09/sports/world-cup-98-from-right-to-left-thuram-sparkles.html|title=WORLD CUP '98; From Right to Left, Thuram Sparkles|work=The New York Times|author1=CHRISTOPHER CLAREY|date=9 July 1998|accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2003/05/15/thuram-zambrotta-perfetti-davids-non-si-ferma.html|title=Thuram e Zambrotta perfetti Davids non si ferma mai|work=La Repubblica|language=Italian|author1=EMANUELE GAMBA|date=15 May 2003|accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/news/newsid=2422410.html|title=Buffon da record, superato Casillas|publisher=UEFA.com|language=Italian|date=24 March 2017|accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref> A large, powerful and versatile player, who was equally competent offensively as he was defensively, he could play on either flank or in the centre, due to his ability with either foot, often alternating between playing as a [[centre-back]] or as a [[Right back (association football)|right-back]], and was even deployed in [[Midfielder|midfield]] on occasion.<ref name=\"Euro 2000 Profile: Lilian Thuram\"/><ref name=\"From Right to Left\"/> In spite of his physical and tenacious playing style, he was also known to be a fair player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1997/04/14/choc-juventus-il-parma-sogna.html|title=CHOC JUVENTUS, IL PARMA SOGNA|work=La Repubblica|language=Italian|author1=Gianni Mura|date=14 April 1997|accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThuram's cousin is [[Le Havre AC|Le Havre]] player [[Yohann Thuram-Ulien]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Transfer window: Charlton sign Yohann Thuram-Ulien |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25729478 |accessdate=27 December 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 January 2014}}</ref> He has two sons with his first wife Sandra, [[Marcus Thuram|Marcus]] (born 6 August 1997) and [[Khephren Thuram|Khephren]] (born January 2001), and both became professional footballers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Monaco: la Juve suivrait Khephren, le 2e fils de Lilian Thuram |url=https://rmcsport.bfmtv.com/football/monaco-la-juve-suivrait-khephren-le-2e-fils-de-lilian-thuram-1306894.html |accessdate=27 December 2018 |date=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThuram is separated from [[Karine Le Marchand]], a French TV host, who registered and then withdrew a complaint of [[domestic violence]] against him.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-09-14/top-stories/42061670_1_domestic-violence-complaint-ex-partner | work=The Times Of India | title=The Times of India: Latest News India, World & Business News, Cricket & Sports, Bollywood}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nThuram was sponsored by sportswear company [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] and appeared in Nike commercials. In a global Nike advertising campaign in the run-up to the 2002 World Cup in Korea and Japan, he starred in a \"[[Secret Tournament]]\" commercial (branded \"Scorpion KO\") directed by [[Terry Gilliam]], appearing alongside football players such as [[Thierry Henry]], [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]], [[Edgar Davids]], [[Fabio Cannavaro]], [[Francesco Totti]], [[Ronaldinho]], [[Lu\u00eds Figo]] and [[Hidetoshi Nakata]], with former player [[Eric Cantona]] the tournament \"referee\".<ref>{{cite news |title=A lighter shoe, cooler kits, a faster ball, a Secret Tournament \u2013 every touch counts |url=http://www.nikebiz.com/story/stry_scorpion.shtml |work=NikeBiz |publisher=Nike |accessdate=21 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020602055510/http://www.nikebiz.com/story/stry_scorpion.shtml |archivedate=2 June 2002 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Claire |last=Cozens |title=Cantona hosts World Cup with a difference |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/apr/03/advertising.worldcupfootball2002?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487 |work=The Guardian |date=3 April 2002 |accessdate=21 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Political engagement==\n[[File:Manif pro mariage LGBT 27012013 15.jpg|thumb|right|Thuram on a 2013 march through Paris by supporters of [[same-sex marriage in France]].]]\nBeyond his football career, Thuram has always shown political engagement, and has frequently spoken out against racism.<ref name=\"Thuram a Treviso contro il razzismo\"/> In such, during the [[2005 French riots|French riots]] in November 2005, Thuram took a position against [[Nicolas Sarkozy]], the head of the conservative political party (and future president) [[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]] and then [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior]]. Thuram was opposed to the verbal attacks against young people that the then-Minister made when he talked about the \"scum\", and he said that Nicolas Sarkozy never lived in a \"banlieue\", areas of low-income housing surrounding French cities.<ref>{{cite news|title=Soccer heroes blame social injustice|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,13509-1865536,00.html |work=[[The Times]]|date=10 November 2005|accessdate=2 December 2006| first1=Charles| last1=Bremner| first2=Adam| last2=Sage}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 September 2006, Thuram sparked controversy when he invited 80 people, who were expelled by French Minister of the Interior Nicolas Sarkozy from a flat where they lived illegally, to the football match between France and Italy.<ref>\n{{cite news|title=Footballer plays political host|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,13509-2346232.html|work=The Times|date=7 September 2006|accessdate=2 December 2006|first=Charles| last=Bremner}}</ref><ref>[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/osm/story/0,,2023499,00.html \"If you can keep a cool head\"]. ''[[The Guardian]]''. Retrieved 30 June 2012.</ref> He has also engaged in campaigns that favour the [[Catalan language]] in [[Northern Catalonia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://paper.avui.cat/article//societat//49512/oleguer/thuram/presentaran/manifest/suport/catala/la/catalunya/nord.html |title=Oleguer and Thuram to present a manifesto supporting Catalan in Northern Catalonia |work=[[Avui]] |language=Catalan |date=10 March 2007 |accessdate=2 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617040620/http://paper.avui.cat/article/societat/49512/oleguer/thuram/presentaran/manifest/suport/catala/la/catalunya/nord.html |archivedate=17 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Thuram curated an exhibition at the [[Mus\u00e9e du quai Branly]] entitled \"Human Zoos: The Invention of the Savage\". It examined the [[human zoos]] that traced the practice of using colonial subjects as exhibits in zoos and freak shows.<ref>{{cite news|title=Paris show unveils life in human zoo|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/nov/29/huam-zoo-paris-exhibition|work=The Guardian|date=29 November 2011|accessdate=29 November 2011| first=Angelique | last=Chrisafis|location=London}}</ref> The material in the exhibition runs from the parade of Brazil's [[Tup\u00ed people|Tupinamba \"savages\"]] for the royal entrance of King [[Henry II of France]] in 1550 in [[Rouen]], to the last \"living spectacle\" of [[Kingdom of Kongo|Congo]] villagers exhibited in [[Brussels]] in 1958.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quaibranly.fr/en/programmation/exhibitions/currently/human-zoos.html |title=Current exhibitions: Human zoos |date=22 November 2011 |accessdate=1 December 2011 |publisher=Mus\u00e9e du quai Branly |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111201162816/http://www.quaibranly.fr/en/programmation/exhibitions/currently/human-zoos.html |archivedate= 1 December 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Thuram took part in a march through Paris by supporters of the [[Ayrault government]]'s plan to [[Same-sex marriage in France|legalise same-sex marriage]].<ref>[http://www.france24.com/fr/20130127-mariage-tous-125000-partisans-gay-defile-paris-prefecture-projet-loi-paris-homosexualite \"Mariage pour tous : entre 125 000 et 400 000 personnes ont d\u00e9fil\u00e9 \u00e0 Paris\"], [[Agence France-Presse]], 27 January 2013</ref> He had previously explained that he supported same-sex marriage in the name of equal rights (comparing the denial of equality for homosexuals to the denial of equal rights for women and for black people in earlier periods of history), and in the name of France's secular principles (''[[la\u00efcit\u00e9]]''), rejecting religious arguments against civil marriage. He also expressed support for the right of same-sex couples to adopt children.<ref>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/Article/ARTJAWEB20130125174821/france-religion-racisme-lilian-thurammariage-gay-lilian-thuram-il-faut-preserver-cette-societe-laique-qui-pense-l-egalite-pour-tous.html \"Mariage gay \u2013 Lilian Thuram : \"Il faut pr\u00e9server cette soci\u00e9t\u00e9 la\u00efque, qui pense l'\u00e9galit\u00e9 pour tous\"], ''[[Jeune Afrique]]'', 25 January 2013</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n[[File:FC Barcelona 2007 cropped.jpg|thumb|right|Thuram ''(back; third from right)'' in the line-up for [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], 2007]]\n\n===Club===\n:Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.joueurs.lilian.thuram.342.en.html|title=Lilian Thuram career statistics|accessdate=10 July 2012|work=Football Database.eu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legaseriea.it/en/serie-a-tim/calciatore?p_p_id=BDC_dettaglio_calciatore_WAR_LegaCalcioBDC&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_col_id=column-1&p_p_col_count=1&_BDC_dettaglio_calciatore_WAR_LegaCalcioBDC_idPersona=12972 |title=Lilian Thuram Serie A stats |accessdate=9 February 2013 |work=LegaSerieA.it |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209222736/http://www.legaseriea.it/en/serie-a-tim/calciatore?p_p_id=BDC_dettaglio_calciatore_WAR_LegaCalcioBDC&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_col_id=column-1&p_p_col_count=1&_BDC_dettaglio_calciatore_WAR_LegaCalcioBDC_idPersona=12972 |archivedate= 9 February 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/players/thuram-in-ec.html|title=Lilian Ulien Thuram \u2013 Matches in European Cups|accessdate=18 April 2013|publisher=RSSSF}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]||[[1990\u201391 French Division 1|1990\u201391]]||rowspan=\"6\"|[[Ligue 1|Division 1]]||1||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[1991\u201392 French Division 1|1991\u201392]]||19||0||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||0||27||0\n|-\n|[[1992\u201393 French Division 1|1992\u201393]]||37||0||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||0||43||0\n|-\n|[[1993\u201394 French Division 1|1993\u201394]]||25||1||3||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||8||1||36||3\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 French Division 1|1994\u201395]]||37||2||2||0||3||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||42||3\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 French Division 1|1995\u201396]]||36||5||3||0||