=See also==\n* [[Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Turkey]]\n* [[Coronavirus Scientific Advisory Board (Turkey)]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Northern Cyprus]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Turkey|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Category:COVID-19 pandemic in Turkey}}\n* Data and maps, frequently updated:\n** {{Cite web |url=https://coronavirus-global.com/turkey |title=Coronavirus Turkey updates and news |language=English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Italian, Swedish, Norwegian, Finnish, Estonian, Russian |trans-title=Latest news and statistics of coronavirus in Turkey. |access-date=4 April 2020}}\n* Government-issued information:\n** [https://covid19bilgi.saglik.gov.tr/tr/ COVID-19] on the [[Ministry of Health (Turkey)|Turkish Ministry of Health]] website\n** [https://covid19.saglik.gov.tr/ COVID-19 cases] on the Turkish Ministry of Health website\n** [https://covid19.tubitak.gov.tr/ COVID-19 Turkey Web Portal] on [[T\u00dcB\u0130TAK]]\n** [https://corona.cbddo.gov.tr/ COVID-19 World Map] on the Digital Conversion Office of the President of Republic of Turkey\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Turkey| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Turkey]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Turkey]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Turkey]]\n[[Category:2020 in Turkey|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Easternmagic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1\u201310 April", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Turkey"}
{"title_page": "Franklin v. Parke-Davis", "text_new": "{{Infobox United States District Court case\n| name               = Franklin v. Parke-Davis\n| court              = [[United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts]]\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| full name          = United States of America ex rel. David Franklin v. Parke-Davis, Division of Warner-Lambert Company\n| date decided       = August 22, 2003\n| docket             = [https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/4276535/franklin-v-parke-davis/ 1:96-cv-11651]\n| citations          = 2003 [[Westlaw|WL]] 22048255\n| transcripts        = \n| judge              = [[Patti B. Saris]]\n| prosecutor         = \n| counsel for plaintiff=\n| plaintiff          =\n| defendant          = \n| prior actions      = Motion to dismiss granted in part, denied in part, 147 [[F. Supp. 2d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/2001186147fsupp2d391180 39] (D. Mass. 2001); protective order modified, 210 F.R.D. 257 (D. Mass. 2002).\n| subsequent actions = \n| holding            = Off-label promotion of pharmaceutical products which causes false claims for payment under the federal [[Medicaid]] program is a valid theory of recovery under the [[False Claims Act]].\n| keywords           = False Claims Act\n}}\n\n'''''Franklin v. Parke-Davis''''' is a lawsuit filed in 1996 against [[Parke-Davis]], a division of [[Warner-Lambert]] Company, and eventually against [[Pfizer]] (which bought Warner-Lambert in 2000)  under the ''[[qui tam]]'' provisions of the [[False Claims Act]].<ref name=2003decision>U.S. ex rel. Franklin v. Parke-Davis, Div. of Warner-Lambert Co., No. CIV.A.96\u201311651PBS, 2003 WL 22048255, at *1 (D. Mass. \nAug. 22, 2003) [http://cyber.law.harvard.edu/cyberlaw2005/sites/cyberlaw2005/images/Neurontin_Memorandum_and_Order.pdf 2003 Decision]</ref> The suit was commenced by [[David Franklin (scientist)|David Franklin]], a [[microbiologist]] hired in the spring of 1996 in a sales capacity at [[Parke-Davis]], a pharmaceutical subsidiary of Warner-Lambert (Warner-Lambert was subsequently acquired by Pfizer in 2000).<ref name=petersen>Melody Petersen, ''Our Daily Meds: How the Pharmaceutical Companies Transformed Themselves into Slick Marketing Machines and Hooked the Nation on Prescription Drugs'', New York: Sarah Crichton Books (2008).</ref> In denying the defendants' motion for [[summary judgment]], the court for the first time recognized [[Off-label use|off-label]] promotion of drugs could cause Medicaid to pay for prescriptions that were not reimbursable, triggering False Claims Act liability. The case was also significant in exposing the degree to which [[publication bias]] impacts the randomized controlled studies conducted by pharmaceutical companies to test the efficacy of their products.<ref name=petersen /> Ultimately, the parties reached a settlement agreement of $430 million to resolve all civil claims and criminal charges stemming from the ''[[qui tam]]'' complaint.<ref name=\"justice\">{{cite web|title=Press Release: Warner-Lambert to Pay $430 Million to Resolve Criminal & Civil Health Care Liability Relating to Off-Label Promotion|url=http://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/2004/May/04_civ_322.htm|publisher=US Department of Justice|language=en|date=May 13, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Krautkramer|first1=Christian J.|title=Neurontin and Off-Label Marketing|journal=The Virtual Mentor|date=1 June 2006|volume=8|issue=6|pages=397\u2013402|doi=10.1001/virtualmentor.2006.8.6.hlaw1-0606|pmid=23234671}}</ref> At the time of the settlement in May 2004, it represented one of the [[List of largest pharmaceutical settlements in the United States|largest False Claims Act recoveries against a pharmaceutical company]] in U.S. history, and was the first [[List of off-label promotion pharmaceutical settlements|off-label promotion settlement]] under the False Claims Act.<ref name=Joseph>Joseph JN, et al. [http://www.postschell.com/site/files/415.pdf  Enforcement Related to Off-Label Marketing and Use of Drugs and Devices: Where Have We Been and Where Are We Going?] Journal of Health & Life Sciences Law 2(2):73-108.  January 2009</ref><ref name=Torberg>David S. Torborg [http://engagedscholarship.csuohio.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1340&context=jlh The Dark Side of the Boom: The Peculiar Dilemma of Modern False Claims Act Litigation]  26 J.L. & Health 181 (2013)</ref>{{rp|194}}\n\n==Factual Background==\n\nAfter four months of employment at Parke-Davis, Franklin became disillusioned by what he believed to be the company's illegal marketing practices in connection with sales of the drug [[Gabapentin|Neurontin]].\n\nIn December 1993, the [[Food and Drug Administration|Food and Drug Administration (FDA)]] had approved Neurontin as a secondary course of treatment for [[epilepsy]], to be used only when the first medication had not brought the epileptic seizures entirely under control.<ref name=Mack>{{cite journal | last1 = Mack | first1 = A | year = 2003 | title = Examination of the evidence for off-label use of gabapentin | url = http://www.amcp.org/data/jmcp/Contemporary%20Subject-559-568.pdf | format = PDF | journal = J Manag Care Pharm | volume = 9 | issue = 6| pages = 559\u201368 | pmid = 14664664 }}</ref> Warner-Lambert executives found the potential revenue in that indication was too low, and decided to promote Neurontin for additional indications, for which the drug was not approved by the FDA and for which there was little to no evidence, including [[migraines]], [[bipolar disorder]] and [[attention-deficit disorder]].<ref name=DFspeaks/>  Members of the Parke-Davis sales team, including [[Medical science liaison|medical liaisons]] like Franklin, were hired to conduct this marketing. Franklin also alleged that physicians and other health care providers were paid illegal [[Kickback (bribery)|kickbacks]] as a ''[[quid pro quo]]'' for prescribing Neurontin, including expensive meals, stays at luxury resorts, and cash payments<ref name=\"BMJ_20030322\">{{cite journal |author=Lenzer J |title=Whistleblower charges drug company with deceptive practices |journal=BMJ |volume=326 |issue=7390 |pages=620 |date=2003-03-22 |pmid=12649230 |pmc=1125531 |doi=10.1136/bmj.326.7390.620 |url=}}</ref> and that Parke-Davis hired ad agencies and marketing firms to produce articles about gabapentin describing the drug's emerging uses and recruited physicians and paid them to sign their names to the ghost written articles as authors.<ref name=\"BMJ_20030322\"/>\n\nAccording to Franklin, a [[case report]] stating that Neurontin had made a child's [[attention deficit disorder]] worse, and his supervisor's dismissal of the report, was a key factor in his decision to leave Parke-Davis in July 1996 after only four months of employment.<ref name=DFspeaks>Melody Petersen for the New York Times. March 12, 2003 [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/03/12/business/12DRUG.html Doctor Explains Why He Blew the Whistle at Pfizer]</ref>  He also reported being told by a supervisor that his career would be threatened or ended if he continued to raise objections, and this is what finally prompted him to quit and hire a Boston attorney, Thomas M. Greene.<ref name=DFspeaks/>\n\n==Lawsuit==\n\nIn August 1996, Franklin and attorney Thomas Greene filed a ''qui tam'' complaint in the [[United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts]] in Boston under the [[False Claims Act]], a federal statute which permits private citizen-whistleblowers (also known as \"relators\") to sue on behalf of the federal government for fraud involving federal money.<ref name=Decision2001>{{cite court |litigants=Franklin v. Parke-Davis |vol=147 |reporter=F. Supp. 2d |opinion=39 |pinpoint= |court=D. Mass. |date=2001 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/2001186147fsupp2d391180 |accessdate=2019-04-01 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nFranklin's suit proposed a novel theory, that Warner-Lambert had perpetrated a fraud against the federal government by causing doctors and patients to submit claims for reimbursement to  Medicaid that Medicaid should not pay for, since by law, Medicaid only pays for treatments that are either approved by the FDA, or are otherwise \"medically accepted\" (as evidenced, for instance, by being included in an [[Formulary (pharmacy)|approved list of drugs and their uses]]).<ref name=HH2003>Hogan & Hartson LLP.  June 2003.  FDA Update: Government Files \"Statement Of Interest\" in Neurontin Off-Label Promotion Case</ref><ref>Greene LLP [http://www.greenellp.com/our-cases/business-cases/false-claim-act-cases/franklin-v-parke-davis-off-label-case-false-claims-act/ Franklin v. Parke-Davis: First Off-Label Case Under False Claims Act] Page accessed August 8, 2014</ref><ref>Stephanie M. Greene \n[http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1478076 False Claims Act Liability for Off-Label Promotion of Pharmaceutical Products]. Penn State Law Review, Vol. 110, pp. 41-68, 2005</ref> The suit also alleged that Warner-Lambert had broken federal [[Kickback (bribery)|kickback]] laws.\n\nThe suit remained sealed for three years while the Department of Justice decided if it would intervene and take over the case, which it had the right to do under the [[False Claims Act]]. In 1999, the government declined, and the case moved forward.<ref name=HH2003/> The defendants sought to have the complaint dismissed, arguing that the causal link between any representations made by Parke-Davis sales representatives and reimbursements for off-label Neurontin prescriptions was too remote.<ref>''Franklin'' at *4</ref> Furthermore, Warner-Lambert argued that Franklin could only prove the pharmaceutical company's liability by showing that Parke-Davis sales liaisons made fraudulent misrepresentations about the drug, as opposed to merely engaging in truthful off-label promotion.<ref>''Franklin'' at *1</ref>\n\nIn an opinion handed down on August 22, 2003, District Judge [[Patti B. Saris]] agreed with David Franklin, denying Warner Lambert's [[summary judgment]] motion to dismiss the lawsuit. Judge Saris found that, if it could be proven that the off-label marketing of Neurontin caused doctors to prescribe the drug and submit prescriptions to Medicaid, then the company would indeed be liable under the False Claims Act. In addition, Judge Saris found that the submission of false Medicaid claims was a foreseeable result of Warner-Lambert's marketing scheme.<ref>''Franklin'' at *4-*5</ref> The case established for the first time that drug companies could be held liable under the False Claims Act for off-label promotion of pharmaceutical products.\n\n==Settlement==\n\nOn May 13, 2004, the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] announced that it had reached an agreement with Warner-Lambert and Pfizer. Warner-Lambert agreed to pay $430 million to resolve criminal and civil liability related to the off-label promotion of [[Gabapentin|Neurontin]], and also agreed to plead guilty to two felony counts of misbranding drugs under the [[Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act]], resulting in a $240 million criminal fine.<ref name=\"justice\" /> Civil damages under the False Claims Act were paid out to the federal government in the amount of $83.6 million, and damages paid out to the states totaled $106.4 million. Relator David Franklin was awarded one of the highest shares ever under the False Claims Act, 29.5% of the settlement, in recognition of his important role in exposing the illicit marketing scheme.<ref name=\"justice\" /> Pfizer agreed to institute a corporate compliance program as part of the settlement.<ref name=\"justice\" /> Also as part of the settlement the [[Consumer & Prescriber Grant Program]] was established to fund public programs to raise awareness of problems with pharmaceutical advertising.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rutkow|first1=Lainie|last2=Teret|first2=Stephen|title=The Potential for State Attorneys General to Promote the Public's Health: Theory, Evidence, and Practice|url=https://folio.iupui.edu/bitstream/handle/10244/953/5107.72048.pdf;jsessionid=96A5C7F3B621CD8DE2077420136A8FC5?sequence=1|publisher=Robert Wood Johnson Foundation Public Health Law Research Program, via FOLIO|date=October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n{{main|List of off-label promotion pharmaceutical settlements|List of largest pharmaceutical settlements in the United States}}\nSince the settlement in 2004, whistleblowers and the federal government have prosecuted numerous off-label promotion cases under the False Claims Act using this case as a precedent.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kesselheim|first1=AS|last2=Darby|first2=D|last3=Studdert|first3=DM|last4=Glynn|first4=R|last5=Levin|first5=R|last6=Avorn|first6=J|title=False Claims Act prosecution did not deter off-label drug use in the case of neurontin.|journal=Health Affairs (Project Hope)|date=December 2011|volume=30|issue=12|pages=2318\u201327|doi=10.1377/hlthaff.2011.0370|pmid=22147859|url=http://content.healthaffairs.org/content/30/12/2318.full|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nSubsequent research reported that the wrongful promotion of the drug was planned by integrating it into [[Continuing medical education]], supporting consultants and members of medical [[advisory boards]] to recommend the use to institutions, and paying people to write about the drug in any positive context including in [[academic literature]], [[letters to the editor]], and managing the [[STEPS trial]] as a [[seeding trial]].<ref name=\"Steinman2006\">{{cite journal|last1=Steinman|first1=Michael A.|title=Narrative Review: The Promotion of Gabapentin: An Analysis of Internal Industry Documents|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|volume=145|issue=4|year=2006|pages=284\u201393|issn=0003-4819|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-145-4-200608150-00008|pmid=16908919|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nLitigation around the marketing of [[ethyl eicosapentaenoic acid]] (branded as \"Vascepa\") by [[Amarin Corporation]] led to a 2015 court decision that changed the FDA's approach to [[off-label marketing]].<ref>Andrew Pollack for the New York Times. 7 August 2015 [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/08/business/court-forbids-fda-from-blocking-truthful-promotion-of-drug.html?_r=0 Court Forbids F.D.A. From Blocking Truthful Promotion of Drug]</ref><ref>Katie Thomas for the New York Times. 8 March 2016 [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/09/business/fda-deal-allows-amarin-to-promote-drug-for-off-label-use.html F.D.A. Deal Allows Amarin to Promote Drug for Off-Label Use]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*\n*\n*\n*\n\n<!-- This will add a notice to the bottom of the page and won't blank it! The new template which says that your draft is waiting for a review will appear at the bottom; simply ignore the old (grey) drafted templates and the old (red) decline templates. A bot will update your article submission. Until then, please don't change anything in this text box and press \"Save page\". -->\n\n[[Category:United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts cases]]\n[[Category:Pfizer]]\n[[Category:2003 in United States case law]]\n[[Category:Drug advertising]]\n[[Category:Off-label drug use]]\n[[Category:Fraud in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox United States District Court case\n| name               = Franklin v. Parke-Davis\n| court              = [[United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts]]\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| full name          = United States of America ex rel. David Franklin v. Parke-Davis, Division of Warner-Lambert Company\n| date decided       = August 22, 2003\n| docket             = [https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/4276535/franklin-v-parke-davis/ 1:96-cv-11651]\n| citations          = 2003 [[Westlaw|WL]] 22048255\n| transcripts        = \n| judge              = [[Patti B. Saris]]\n| prosecutor         = \n| counsel for plaintiff=\n| plaintiff          =\n| defendant          = \n| prior actions      = Motion to dismiss granted in part, denied in part, 147 [[F. Supp. 2d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/2001186147fsupp2d391180 39] (D. Mass. 2001); protective order modified, 210 F.R.D. 257 (D. Mass. 2002).\n| subsequent actions = \n| holding            = Off-label promotion of pharmaceutical products which causes false claims for payment under the federal [[Medicaid]] program is a valid theory of recovery under the [[False Claims Act]].\n| keywords           = False Claims Act\n}}\n\n'''''Franklin v. Parke-Davis''''' is a lawsuit filed in 1996 against [[Parke-Davis]], a division of [[Warner-Lambert]] Company, and eventually against [[Pfizer]] (which bought Warner-Lambert in 2000)  under the ''[[qui tam]]'' provisions of the [[False Claims Act]].<ref name=2003decision>U.S. ex rel. Franklin v. Parke-Davis, Div. of Warner-Lambert Co., No. CIV.A.96\u201311651PBS, 2003 WL 22048255, at *1 (D. Mass. \nAug. 22, 2003) [http://cyber.law.harvard.edu/cyberlaw2005/sites/cyberlaw2005/images/Neurontin_Memorandum_and_Order.pdf 2003 Decision]</ref> The suit was commenced by [[David Franklin (scientist)|David Franklin]], a [[microbiologist]] hired in the spring of 1996 in a sales capacity at [[Parke-Davis]], a pharmaceutical subsidiary of Warner-Lambert (Warner-Lambert was subsequently acquired by Pfizer in 2000).<ref name=petersen>Melody Petersen, ''Our Daily Meds: How the Pharmaceutical Companies Transformed Themselves into Slick Marketing Machines and Hooked the Nation on Prescription Drugs'', New York: Sarah Crichton Books (2008).</ref> In denying the defendants' motion for [[summary judgment]], the court for the first time recognized [[Off-label use|off-label]] promotion of drugs could cause Medicaid to pay for prescriptions that were not reimbursable, triggering False Claims Act liability. The case was also significant in exposing the degree to which [[publication bias]] impacts the randomized controlled studies conducted by pharmaceutical companies to test the efficacy of their products.<ref name=petersen /> Ultimately, the parties reached a settlement agreement of $430 million to resolve all civil claims and criminal charges stemming from the ''[[qui tam]]'' complaint.<ref name=\"justice\">{{cite web|title=Press Release: Warner-Lambert to Pay $430 Million to Resolve Criminal & Civil Health Care Liability Relating to Off-Label Promotion|url=http://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/2004/May/04_civ_322.htm|publisher=US Department of Justice|language=en|date=May 13, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Krautkramer|first1=Christian J.|title=Neurontin and Off-Label Marketing|journal=The Virtual Mentor|date=1 June 2006|volume=8|issue=6|pages=397\u2013402|doi=10.1001/virtualmentor.2006.8.6.hlaw1-0606|pmid=23234671}}</ref> At the time of the settlement in May 2004, it represented one of the [[List of largest pharmaceutical settlements in the United States|largest False Claims Act recoveries against a pharmaceutical company]] in U.S. history, and was the first [[List of off-label promotion pharmaceutical settlements|off-label promotion settlement]] under the False Claims Act.<ref name=Joseph>Joseph JN, et al. [http://www.postschell.com/site/files/415.pdf  Enforcement Related to Off-Label Marketing and Use of Drugs and Devices: Where Have We Been and Where Are We Going?] Journal of Health & Life Sciences Law 2(2):73-108.  January 2009</ref><ref name=Torberg>David S. Torborg [http://engagedscholarship.csuohio.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1340&context=jlh The Dark Side of the Boom: The Peculiar Dilemma of Modern False Claims Act Litigation]  26 J.L. & Health 181 (2013</ref>{{rp|194}}\n\n==Factual Background==\n\nAfter four months of employment at Parke-Davis, Franklin became disillusioned by what he believed to be the company's illegal marketing practices in connection with sales of the drug [[Gabapentin|Neurontin]].\n\nIn December 1993, the [[Food and Drug Administration|Food and Drug Administration (FDA)]] had approved Neurontin as a secondary course of treatment for [[epilepsy]], to be used only when the first medication had not brought the epileptic seizures entirely under control.<ref name=Mack>Mack A. [http://www.amcp.org/data/jmcp/Contemporary%20Subject-559-568.pdf Examination of the evidence for off-label use of gabapentin] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917222044/http://amcp.org/data/jmcp/Contemporary%20Subject-559-568.pdf |date=2010-09-17 }}. J Manag Care Pharm. 2003 Nov-Dec;9(6):559-68. {{PMID|14664664}}</ref> Warner-Lambert executives found the potential revenue in that indication was too low, and decided to promote Neurontin for additional indications, for which the drug was not approved by the FDA and for which there was little to no evidence, including [[migraines]], [[bipolar disorder]] and [[attention-deficit disorder]].<ref name=DFspeaks/>  Members of the Parke-Davis sales team, including [[Medical science liaison|medical liaisons]] like Franklin, were hired to conduct this marketing. Franklin also alleged that physicians and other health care providers were paid illegal [[Kickback (bribery)|kickbacks]] as a ''[[quid pro quo]]'' for prescribing Neurontin, including expensive meals, stays at luxury resorts, and cash payments<ref name=\"BMJ_20030322\">{{cite journal |author=Lenzer J |title=Whistleblower charges drug company with deceptive practices |journal=BMJ |volume=326 |issue=7390 |pages=620 |date=2003-03-22 |pmid=12649230 |pmc=1125531 |doi=10.1136/bmj.326.7390.620 |url=}}</ref> and that Parke-Davis hired ad agencies and marketing firms to produce articles about gabapentin describing the drug's emerging uses and recruited physicians and paid them to sign their names to the ghost written articles as authors.<ref name=\"BMJ_20030322\"/>\n\nAccording to Franklin, a [[case report]] stating that Neurontin had made a child's [[attention deficit disorder]] worse, and his supervisor's dismissal of the report, was a key factor in his decision to leave Parke-Davis in July 1996 after only four months of employment.<ref name=DFspeaks>Melody Petersen for the New York Times. March 12, 2003 [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/03/12/business/12DRUG.html Doctor Explains Why He Blew the Whistle at Pfizer]</ref>  He also reported being told by a supervisor that his career would be threatened or ended if he continued to raise objections, and this is what finally prompted him to quit and hire a Boston attorney, Thomas M. Greene.<ref name=DFspeaks/>\n\n==Lawsuit==\n\nIn August 1996, Franklin and attorney Thomas Greene filed a ''qui tam'' complaint in the [[United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts]] in Boston under the [[False Claims Act]], a federal statute which permits private citizen-whistleblowers (also known as \"relators\") to sue on behalf of the federal government for fraud involving federal money.<ref name=Decision2001>{{cite court |litigants=Franklin v. Parke-Davis |vol=147 |reporter=F. Supp. 2d |opinion=39 |pinpoint= |court=D. Mass. |date=2001 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/2001186147fsupp2d391180 |accessdate=2019-04-01 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nFranklin's suit proposed a novel theory, that Warner-Lambert had perpetrated a fraud against the federal government by causing doctors and patients to submit claims for reimbursement to  Medicaid that Medicaid should not pay for, since by law, Medicaid only pays for treatments that are either approved by the FDA, or are otherwise \"medically accepted\" (as evidenced, for instance, by being included in an [[Formulary (pharmacy)|approved list of drugs and their uses]]).<ref name=HH2003>Hogan & Hartson LLP.  June 2003.  FDA Update: Government Files \"Statement Of Interest\" in Neurontin Off-Label Promotion Case</ref><ref>Greene LLP [http://www.greenellp.com/our-cases/business-cases/false-claim-act-cases/franklin-v-parke-davis-off-label-case-false-claims-act/ Franklin v. Parke-Davis: First Off-Label Case Under False Claims Act] Page accessed August 8, 2014</ref><ref>Stephanie M. Greene \n[http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1478076 False Claims Act Liability for Off-Label Promotion of Pharmaceutical Products]. Penn State Law Review, Vol. 110, pp. 41-68, 2005</ref> The suit also alleged that Warner-Lambert had broken federal [[Kickback (bribery)|kickback]] laws.\n\nThe suit remained sealed for three years while the Department of Justice decided if it would intervene and take over the case, which it had the right to do under the [[False Claims Act]]. In 1999, the government declined, and the case moved forward.<ref name=HH2003/> The defendants sought to have the complaint dismissed, arguing that the causal link between any representations made by Parke-Davis sales representatives and reimbursements for off-label Neurontin prescriptions was too remote.<ref>''Franklin'' at *4</ref> Furthermore, Warner-Lambert argued that Franklin could only prove the pharmaceutical company's liability by showing that Parke-Davis sales liaisons made fraudulent misrepresentations about the drug, as opposed to merely engaging in truthful off-label promotion.<ref>''Franklin'' at *1</ref>\n\nIn an opinion handed down on August 22, 2003, District Judge [[Patti B. Saris]] agreed with David Franklin, denying Warner Lambert's [[summary judgment]] motion to dismiss the lawsuit. Judge Saris found that, if it could be proven that the off-label marketing of Neurontin caused doctors to prescribe the drug and submit prescriptions to Medicaid, then the company would indeed be liable under the False Claims Act. In addition, Judge Saris found that the submission of false Medicaid claims was a foreseeable result of Warner-Lambert's marketing scheme.<ref>''Franklin'' at *4-*5</ref> The case established for the first time that drug companies could be held liable under the False Claims Act for off-label promotion of pharmaceutical products.\n\n==Settlement==\n\nOn May 13, 2004, the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] announced that it had reached an agreement with Warner-Lambert and Pfizer. Warner-Lambert agreed to pay $430 million to resolve criminal and civil liability related to the off-label promotion of [[Gabapentin|Neurontin]], and also agreed to plead guilty to two felony counts of misbranding drugs under the [[Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act]], resulting in a $240 million criminal fine.<ref name=\"justice\" /> Civil damages under the False Claims Act were paid out to the federal government in the amount of $83.6 million, and damages paid out to the states totaled $106.4 million. Relator David Franklin was awarded one of the highest shares ever under the False Claims Act, 29.5% of the settlement, in recognition of his important role in exposing the illicit marketing scheme.<ref name=\"justice\" /> Pfizer agreed to institute a corporate compliance program as part of the settlement.<ref name=\"justice\" /> Also as part of the settlement the [[Consumer & Prescriber Grant Program]] was established to fund public programs to raise awareness of problems with pharmaceutical advertising.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rutkow|first1=Lainie|last2=Teret|first2=Stephen|title=The Potential for State Attorneys General to Promote the Public's Health: Theory, Evidence, and Practice|url=https://folio.iupui.edu/bitstream/handle/10244/953/5107.72048.pdf;jsessionid=96A5C7F3B621CD8DE2077420136A8FC5?sequence=1|publisher=Robert Wood Johnson Foundation Public Health Law Research Program, via FOLIO|date=October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n{{main|List of off-label promotion pharmaceutical settlements|List of largest pharmaceutical settlements in the United States}}\nSince the settlement in 2004, whistleblowers and the federal government have prosecuted numerous off-label promotion cases under the False Claims Act using this case as a precedent.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kesselheim|first1=AS|last2=Darby|first2=D|last3=Studdert|first3=DM|last4=Glynn|first4=R|last5=Levin|first5=R|last6=Avorn|first6=J|title=False Claims Act prosecution did not deter off-label drug use in the case of neurontin.|journal=Health Affairs (Project Hope)|date=December 2011|volume=30|issue=12|pages=2318\u201327|doi=10.1377/hlthaff.2011.0370|pmid=22147859|url=http://content.healthaffairs.org/content/30/12/2318.full|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nSubsequent research reported that the wrongful promotion of the drug was planned by integrating it into [[Continuing medical education]], supporting consultants and members of medical [[advisory boards]] to recommend the use to institutions, and paying people to write about the drug in any positive context including in [[academic literature]], [[letters to the editor]], and managing the [[STEPS trial]] as a [[seeding trial]].<ref name=\"Steinman2006\">{{cite journal|last1=Steinman|first1=Michael A.|title=Narrative Review: The Promotion of Gabapentin: An Analysis of Internal Industry Documents|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|volume=145|issue=4|year=2006|pages=284\u201393|issn=0003-4819|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-145-4-200608150-00008|pmid=16908919|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nLitigation around the marketing of [[ethyl eicosapentaenoic acid]] (branded as \"Vascepa\") by [[Amarin Corporation]] led to a 2015 court decision that changed the FDA's approach to [[off-label marketing]].<ref>Andrew Pollack for the New York Times. 7 August 2015 [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/08/business/court-forbids-fda-from-blocking-truthful-promotion-of-drug.html?_r=0 Court Forbids F.D.A. From Blocking Truthful Promotion of Drug]</ref><ref>Katie Thomas for the New York Times. 8 March 2016 [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/09/business/fda-deal-allows-amarin-to-promote-drug-for-off-label-use.html F.D.A. Deal Allows Amarin to Promote Drug for Off-Label Use]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*\n*\n*\n*\n\n<!-- This will add a notice to the bottom of the page and won't blank it! The new template which says that your draft is waiting for a review will appear at the bottom; simply ignore the old (grey) drafted templates and the old (red) decline templates. A bot will update your article submission. Until then, please don't change anything in this text box and press \"Save page\". -->\n\n[[Category:United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts cases]]\n[[Category:Pfizer]]\n[[Category:2003 in United States case law]]\n[[Category:Drug advertising]]\n[[Category:Off-label drug use]]\n[[Category:Fraud in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franklin_v._Parke-Davis"}
{"title_page": "Melody Davidson", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Melody Davidson\n| image        = Melody Davidson.jpg\n| alt          = \n| caption      = Davidson in 2010\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth based on age as of date|55|2018|7|26|mos=1}}<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/article-gina-kingsbury-takes-over-management-of-canadas-womens-hockey-team/]</ref>\n| birth_place  =[[Coronation, Alberta]], Canada\n| death_date   = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place  = \n| spouse(s)    = \n| education    = [[Red Deer College]] <br> [[University of Alberta]]\n| occupation   = [[Coach (ice hockey)|Ice hockey coach]]\n| years_active = \n| known_for    = \n| awards       = \n}}\n\n'''Melody Davidson''' (born 1962 or 1963) was the [[head coach]] of the [[Canada women's national ice hockey team|Canadian national women's hockey team]]. She was the head coach of the gold medal winning [[2006 Winter Olympics]] and [[2010 Winter Olympics]] Canadian women's team.\n\nA graduate of the [[University of Alberta]], she was also the head coach of the [[Cornell Big Red women's ice hockey]] team. Previously the head coach of the Connecticut College Camels women's ice hockey team.\n\n==Early life and education==\nDavidson was born in [[Coronation, Alberta]] but moved to [[Oyen, Alberta]] after grade 3.<ref>{{cite web |title=2009 - MELODY DAVIDSON |url=http://www.clearview.ab.ca/view.php?action=object&id=261&stream=Award%20of%20Merit |website=clearview.ab.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> After high school,  she attended [[Red Deer College]], where she earned a degree in physical education, and the [[University of Alberta]] (U of A).<ref>{{cite web |title=Melody Davidson - RDC's 2006 Distinguished Alum |url=https://rdc.ab.ca/about/alumni-foundation/alumni/blog/melody-davidson-rdcs-2006-distinguished-alum |website=rdc.ab.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> With her bachelor's degree, Davidson accepted a position as a recreation director before attending the National Coaching Institute at the [[University of Calgary]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The coaching champion |url=https://medium.com/ualberta2017/as-a-trailblazing-coach-mentor-and-administrator-melody-davidson-86-bpe-has-played-a-bd41aded6d6a |website=medium.com |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=January 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDavidson began coaching her brothers hockey team in 1978 and eventually graduated to women's hockey in 1989. As a coach, she led Team Alberta at the 1991, 1995 and 1999 Canada Winter Games.<ref name = \"ashfm\">{{cite web |title=Melody Davidson |url=https://ashfm.ca/hall-of-fame-honoured-members/browse/hockey/davidson-melody |website=ashfm.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> As a result, she was asked to be an assistant coach for the [[Canada women's national ice hockey team|Canadian national women's hockey team]] at the [[2002 Winter Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Women's hockey team renews focus on Olympics |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/women-s-hockey-team-renews-focus-on-olympics-1.265172 |website=cbc.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=November 21, 2001}}</ref> After her Olympic Games experience where Team Canada won gold, she had caught the attention of [[Cornell University]] who offered her a coaching position.<ref>{{cite web |title=Melody Davidson to Coach Cornell Women |url=https://www.uscho.com/2002/08/07/melody-davidson-to-coach-cornell-women/ |website=uscho.com |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=August 7, 2002}}</ref>\n\nAs head coach at Cornell, she was appointed Head Coach of Team Canada for the 2004\u20132005 season,<ref>{{cite web |title=MELODY DAVIDSON NAMED HEAD COACH FOR CANADA\u2019S NATIONAL WOMEN\u2019S HOCKEY TEAM FOR 2004-2005 SEASON AND 2006 WINTER OLYMPICS IN TORINO, ITALY |url=http://www.hockeymanitoba.ca/news/melody-davidson-named-head-coach-for-canadas-national-womens-hockey-team-for-2004-2005-season-and-2006-winter-olympics-in-torino-italy/ |website=hockeymanitoba.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=May 31, 2004}}</ref> the [[2006 Winter Olympics]], where Canada won another gold medal,<ref>{{cite web |title=Cornellian Melody Davidson brings home the gold |url=http://news.cornell.edu/stories/2006/02/olympic-glory-cornellians-olympics |website=news.cornell.edu |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=February 22, 2006}}</ref> and at the [[2010 Winter Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Hockey Coach Melody Davidson Looks Ahead to 2010 |url=https://olympic.ca/2009/05/29/womens-hockey-coach-melody-davidson-looks-ahead-to-2010/ |website=olympic.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=May 29, 2009}}</ref> Her role in the Olympics earned her various honours including being inducted into the [[Alberta Sports Hall of Fame]]<ref name = \"ashfm\"/> and the Canadian Olympic Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |title=Davidson Inducted Into Hall Of Fame |url=https://www.hockeyalberta.ca/news/news-1/davidson-inducted-into-hall-fame-254/ |website=hockeyalberta.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=February 8, 2011}}</ref> She was also awarded the 2010 Jack Donohue Coach of the Year Award and named to the Canadian Association for the Advancement of Women and Sport and Physical Activity's most influential women list.<ref>{{cite web |title=MELODY DAVIDSON NAMED TO CAAWS MOST INFLUENTIAL WOMEN LIST |url=https://www.hockeycanada.ca/en-ca/news/2011-nwt-002-en |website=hockeycanada.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=January 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching record==\n===Cornell University===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:red;\"\n| '''Year''' || '''Wins''' || '''Losses''' ||'''Ties''' ||    '''Postseason'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" bgcolor=\"\"\n| 2004\u201305|| 3 || 22 || 3||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" bgcolor=\"\"\n|2003\u201304 || 7 || 21 || 2||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" bgcolor=\"\"\n|2002\u201303 || 4 || 21 || 2||\n|}<ref>[http://www.uscho.com/stats/coachYxY.php?cid=597&gender=w Statistics :: USCHO.com :: U.S. College Hockey Online]</ref>\n\n==Managerial==\nOn July 26, 2018, it was announced that [[Gina Kingsbury]] would take over Davidson's role as General Manager of the [[Canada women's national ice hockey team]] at [[Hockey Canada]]. Davidson stated that she left the position after eight years to focus on scouting.<ref>{{cite web |url=  https://www.cbc.ca/sports/olympics/hockey/hockey-canada-womens-team-gina-kingsbury-1.4762389|title= Gina Kingsbury takes over Hockey Canada women's team |author=Donna Spencer: The Canadian Press |publisher= Canadian Broadcasting Corporation Sports | accessdate= 26 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davidson, Melody}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alberta Sports Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey coaches]]\n[[Category:Cornell University faculty]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Alberta]]\n[[Category:1960s births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Melody Davidson\n| image        = Melody Davidson.jpg\n| alt          = \n| caption      = Davidson in 2010\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Bbad|55|2018|7|26|mos=1}}<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/article-gina-kingsbury-takes-over-management-of-canadas-womens-hockey-team/]</ref>\n| birth_place  =[[Coronation, Alberta]], Canada\n| death_date   = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place  = \n| spouse(s)    = \n| education    = [[Red Deer College]] <br> [[University of Alberta]]\n| occupation   = [[Coach (ice hockey)|Ice hockey coach]]\n| years_active = \n| known_for    = \n| awards       = \n}}\n\n'''Melody Davidson''' (born 1962 or 1963) was the [[head coach]] of the [[Canada women's national ice hockey team|Canadian national women's hockey team]]. She was the head coach of the gold medal winning [[2006 Winter Olympics]] and [[2010 Winter Olympics]] Canadian women's team.\n\nA graduate of the [[University of Alberta]], she was also the head coach of the [[Cornell Big Red women's ice hockey]] team. Previously the head coach of the Connecticut College Camels women's ice hockey team.\n\n==Early life and education==\nDavidson was born in [[Coronation, Alberta]] but moved to [[Oyen, Alberta]] after grade 3.<ref>{{cite web |title=2009 - MELODY DAVIDSON |url=http://www.clearview.ab.ca/view.php?action=object&id=261&stream=Award%20of%20Merit |website=clearview.ab.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> After high school,  she attended [[Red Deer College]], where she earned a degree in physical education, and the [[University of Alberta]] (U of A).<ref>{{cite web |title=Melody Davidson - RDC's 2006 Distinguished Alum |url=https://rdc.ab.ca/about/alumni-foundation/alumni/blog/melody-davidson-rdcs-2006-distinguished-alum |website=rdc.ab.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> With her bachelors degree, Davidson accepted a position as a recreation director before attending the National Coaching Institute at the [[University of Calgary]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The coaching champion |url=https://medium.com/ualberta2017/as-a-trailblazing-coach-mentor-and-administrator-melody-davidson-86-bpe-has-played-a-bd41aded6d6a |website=medium.com |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=January 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDavidson began coaching her brothers hockey team in 1978 and eventually graduated to women\u2019s hockey in 1989. As a coach, she led Team Alberta at the 1991, 1995 and 1999 Canada Winter Games.<ref name = \"ashfm\">{{cite web |title=Melody Davidson |url=https://ashfm.ca/hall-of-fame-honoured-members/browse/hockey/davidson-melody |website=ashfm.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> As a result, she was asked to be an assistant coach for the [[Canada women's national ice hockey team|Canadian national women's hockey team]] at the [[2002 Winter Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Women's hockey team renews focus on Olympics |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/women-s-hockey-team-renews-focus-on-olympics-1.265172 |website=cbc.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=November 21, 2001}}</ref> After her Olympic Games experience where Team Canada won gold, she had caught the attention of [[Cornell University]] who offered her a coaching position.<ref>{{cite web |title=Melody Davidson to Coach Cornell Women |url=https://www.uscho.com/2002/08/07/melody-davidson-to-coach-cornell-women/ |website=uscho.com |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=August 7, 2002}}</ref>\n\nAs head coach at Cornell, she was appointed Head Coach of Team Canada for the 2004\u20132005 season,<ref>{{cite web |title=MELODY DAVIDSON NAMED HEAD COACH FOR CANADA\u2019S NATIONAL WOMEN\u2019S HOCKEY TEAM FOR 2004-2005 SEASON AND 2006 WINTER OLYMPICS IN TORINO, ITALY |url=http://www.hockeymanitoba.ca/news/melody-davidson-named-head-coach-for-canadas-national-womens-hockey-team-for-2004-2005-season-and-2006-winter-olympics-in-torino-italy/ |website=hockeymanitoba.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=May 31, 2004}}</ref> the [[2006 Winter Olympics]], where Canada won another gold medal,<ref>{{cite web |title=Cornellian Melody Davidson brings home the gold |url=http://news.cornell.edu/stories/2006/02/olympic-glory-cornellians-olympics |website=news.cornell.edu |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=February 22, 2006}}</ref> and at the [[2010 Winter Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Hockey Coach Melody Davidson Looks Ahead to 2010 |url=https://olympic.ca/2009/05/29/womens-hockey-coach-melody-davidson-looks-ahead-to-2010/ |website=olympic.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=May 29, 2009}}</ref> Her role in the Olympics earned her various honours including being inducted into the [[Alberta Sports Hall of Fame]]<ref name = \"ashfm\"/> and the Canadian Olympic Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |title=Davidson Inducted Into Hall Of Fame |url=https://www.hockeyalberta.ca/news/news-1/davidson-inducted-into-hall-fame-254/ |website=hockeyalberta.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=February 8, 2011}}</ref> She was also awarded the 2010 Jack Donohue Coach of the Year Award and named to the Canadian Association for the Advancement of Women and Sport and Physical Activity\u2019s most influential women list.<ref>{{cite web |title=MELODY DAVIDSON NAMED TO CAAWS MOST INFLUENTIAL WOMEN LIST |url=https://www.hockeycanada.ca/en-ca/news/2011-nwt-002-en |website=hockeycanada.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=January 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching record==\n===Cornell University===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:red;\"\n| '''Year''' || '''Wins''' || '''Losses''' ||'''Ties''' ||    '''Postseason'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" bgcolor=\"\"\n| 2004\u201305|| 3 || 22 || 3||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" bgcolor=\"\"\n|2003\u201304 || 7 || 21 || 2||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" bgcolor=\"\"\n|2002\u201303 || 4 || 21 || 2||\n|}<ref>[http://www.uscho.com/stats/coachYxY.php?cid=597&gender=w Statistics :: USCHO.com :: U.S. College Hockey Online]</ref>\n\n==Managerial==\nOn July 26, 2018, it was announced that [[Gina Kingsbury]] would take over Davidson's role as General Manager of the [[Canada women's national ice hockey team]] at [[Hockey Canada]]. Davidson stated that she left the position after eight years to focus on scouting.<ref>{{cite web |url=  https://www.cbc.ca/sports/olympics/hockey/hockey-canada-womens-team-gina-kingsbury-1.4762389|title= Gina Kingsbury takes over Hockey Canada women's team |author=Donna Spencer: The Canadian Press |publisher= Canadian Broadcasting Corporation Sports | accessdate= 26 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davidson, Melody}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alberta Sports Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey coaches]]\n[[Category:Cornell University faculty]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Alberta]]\n[[Category:1960s births]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: bachelors degree \u2192 bachelor's degree, \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melody_Davidson"}
{"title_page": "OpenSCAD", "text_new": "{{Infobox software\n| name = OpenSCAD\n| title = OpenSCAD\n| logo = OpenSCAD-logo.png\n| screenshot = Openscad_screen_english.png\n| caption = OpenSCAD 2015.03\n| collapsible = \n| author = \n| developer = Marius Kintel, Clifford Wolf\n| released = {{Start date|2010|02|19|df=yes/no}}\n| discontinued = \n| latest release version = 2019.05\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2019|05|18|df=yes/no}}\n| latest preview version = <!--2018.11.20<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.openscad.org/downloads.html#snapshots |title=OpenSCAD Development Snapshots}}</ref>-->\n| latest preview date = <!--{{Start date and age|2018|11|20|df=yes/no}}-->\n| programming language = [[C++]] and [[Qt (framework)|Qt]], [[CGAL]], [[OpenCSG]], and [[OpenGL]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/openscad/openscad/blob/master/README.md#building-openscad |title=Building OpenSCAD}}</ref>\n| operating system = [[Linux]], [[OS X]], [[Windows]], [[FreeBSD]], [[NetBSD]], [[OpenBSD]]\n| platform = [[IA-32]], [[x64]]\n| size = 15\u201325 [[Megabyte|MB]] (varies by operating system)<ref>http://www.openscad.org/downloads.html</ref>\n| language count = 7\n| language = Czech, English, French, German, Polish, Russian, Spanish, Magyar\n| genre = [[Computer-aided design|CAD]]\n| license = [[GNU General Public License|GPLv2]]\n| website = {{URL|www.openscad.org}}\n}}\n\n'''OpenSCAD''' is a [[free software]] application for creating solid 3D CAD ([[computer-aided design]]) objects. It is a script-only based modeller that uses its own description language; parts can be previewed, but it cannot be interactively selected or modified by mouse in the 3D view. An OpenSCAD script specifies geometric primitives (such as spheres, boxes, cylinders, etc.) and defines how they are modified and combined (for instance by intersection, difference, envelope combination and [[Minkowski sum]]s) to render a [[3D model]]. As such, the program does [[constructive solid geometry]] (CSG). OpenSCAD is available for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[Linux]] and [[OS X]].\n\n== Previewing ==\nFor fast previewing of models using [[z-buffering]], OpenSCAD employs [[OpenCSG]] and [[OpenGL]].\n\nThe 3D model position can be interactively manipulated in the view with a mouse similarly to other 3D modellers. It is also possible to define a default \"camera\" position in the script.\n\nPart colors can be defined in the 3D view (including transparency).<ref>Transparency is evaluated in the construction order, so a part is only transparent for parts already built.</ref>\n\nPreview is relatively fast and allows interactive modifications while modifying the script.\n\nThe model renderer takes into account lighting, but the lighting source is not modifiable.\n\n== Use ==\nOpenSCAD allows a designer to create accurate 3D models and [[solid modeling#Parametric modeling|parametric designs]] that can be easily adjusted by changing the parameters.<ref>{{citation |first=Brian |last=Evans |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FPSsCTE9KpgC |title=Practical 3D Printers: The Science and Art of 3D Printing |year=2012 |page=113 |publisher=Apress |isbn=9781430243922 }}.</ref>\n\nOpenSCAD documents are human-readable scripts in plain ASCII text.\n\nAs such, OpenSCAD is a programmer-oriented solid-modeling tool<ref>{{citation |first1=Bre |last1=Pettis |first2=Anna Kaziunas |last2=France |first3=Jay |last3=Shergill |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-iaTMXZJQ9cC |title=Getting Started with MakerBot |publisher=O'Reilly Media, Inc. |year=2012 |page=131 |isbn=9781449338657}}.</ref> and has been recommended as an entry-level [[Computer-aided design|CAD]] tool for designing [[open-source hardware]] such as scientific tools for research and education.<ref>{{citation |first=Joshua M. |last=Pearce |authorlink=Joshua Pearce |title=Open-Source Lab: How to Build Your Own Hardware and Reduce Research Costs |publisher=Elsevier |year=2014 |isbn=9780124104624 |chapter=Chapter 6: \u201eDigital Designs and Scientific Hardware\u201c|pages=165\u2013254|title-link=Open-Source Lab (book) }}.</ref>\n\nIt is mostly used to design [[3D printing|3D printed]] parts, which are exported in [[STL (file format)|STL]] format.\n\n[[File:Strandbeest 3d - crank offset corrected.gif|thumb|Animation created with OpenSCAD]]\nAnimation is possible with a speed of a few images per seconds for simple models. The animation can have effect on any parameter, being it the camera position or the parts dimensions, position, shape or existence.\nIt can be recorded as a set of images usable to build films.\n\n== Exportation ==\n* Views can be exported in [[Portable Network Graphics|PNG]] format.\n* 2D models can be exported in [[AutoCAD DXF]].\n* 3D parts can be exported in [[Additive Manufacturing File Format|AMF]], [[OFF (file format)|OFF]], [[STL (file format)|STL]], as simple volumes. There is no color, material nor parts definition in the exported model (July 2016).\n\n== Importation ==\n* 2D drawings in DXF,SVG and PNG can be imported, then extruded as monolithic parts.\n* 3D parts can be imported in STL and can be scaled and submitted to subtractive or additive operations.\n\n== Design ==\nOpenSCAD is a wrapper to a [[Constructive_solid_geometry|CSG]] engine with a graphical user interface and integrated editor, developed in C++. As of 2016, it uses the [[Computational Geometry Algorithms Library]] (CGAL) as its basic CSG engine.\n\nIts script syntax reflects a [[functional programming]] philosophy. Much as in [[Haskell (programming language)|Haskell]], within a scope each \"variable\" is treated as a constant, immutable with at most one value.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n\n* [[List of computer-aided design editors for architecture, engineering and construction]]\n* [[PLaSM]] is another open source scripting language for creating 3D objects\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{wikibooks-inline|OpenSCAD User Manual}}\n* [http://www.shapeoko.com/wiki/index.php/OpenSCAD OpenSCAD page on Shapeoko wiki] \u2014 includes links to supporting utilities, special purpose tools (such as a screw generator) and includes an example of creating a Machinist's diamond, circle, square milling test as a parameterized file suitable for re-creating at any desired size.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n0HMJ_OfzYE&list=PLXFMUfzq5U4QvHGHRwuSr4KmzZBiqW1iP Videos on the basics of modeling with OpenSCAD]\n\n=== Related software ===\n*[http://openjscad.org/  OpenJscad] Web interface for a programmatic modeller with partial compatibility with OpenScad scripts. Developed in Javascript.\n*[http://www.implicitcad.org ImplicitCAD] Script-based modeller with an custom graphic engine. It does have an internal object model. Syntax similar but different from OpenScad. No [[GUI]].\n*[https://github.com/GilesBathgate/RapCAD Rapcad] Programmatic modeller\n*[https://www.blockscad3d.com/editor/ Blockscad3D] [[Blockly]] implementation of OpenSCAD\n\n{{3D software}}\n{{CAD software}}\n\n[[Category:Engineering software that uses Qt]]\n[[Category:3D graphics software]]\n[[Category:Free computer-aided design software]]\n[[Category:Free software programmed in C++]]\n[[Category:Free 3D graphics software]]\n[[Category:3D computer graphics software for Linux]]\n[[Category:Computer-aided design software for Linux]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox software\n| name = OpenSCAD\n| title = OpenSCAD\n| logo = OpenSCAD-logo.png\n| screenshot = Openscad_screen_english.png\n| caption = OpenSCAD 2015.03\n| collapsible = \n| author = \n| developer = Marius Kintel, Clifford Wolf\n| released = {{Start date|2010|02|19|df=yes/no}}\n| discontinued = \n| latest release version = 2019.05\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2019|05|18|df=yes/no}}\n| latest preview version = <!--2018.11.20<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.openscad.org/downloads.html#snapshots |title=OpenSCAD Development Snapshots}}</ref>-->\n| latest preview date = <!--{{Start date and age|2018|11|20|df=yes/no}}-->\n| programming language = [[C++]] and [[Qt (framework)|Qt]], [[CGAL]], [[OpenCSG]], and [[OpenGL]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/openscad/openscad/blob/master/README.md#building-openscad |title=Building OpenSCAD}}</ref>\n| operating system = [[Linux]], [[OS X]], [[Windows]], [[FreeBSD]], [[NetBSD]], [[OpenBSD]]\n| platform = [[IA-32]], [[x64]]\n| size = 15\u201325 [[Megabyte|MB]] (varies by operating system)<ref>http://www.openscad.org/downloads.html</ref>\n| language count = 7\n| language = Czech, English, French, German, Polish, Russian, Spanish, Magyar\n| genre = [[Computer-aided design|CAD]]\n| license = [[GNU General Public License|GPLv2]]\n| website = {{URL|www.openscad.org}}\n}}\n\n'''OpenSCAD''' is a [[free software]] application for creating solid 3D CAD ([[computer-aided design]]) objects. It is a script-only based modeller that uses its own description language; parts can be previewed, but it cannot be interactively selected or modified by mouse in the 3D view. An OpenSCAD script specifies geometric primitives (such as spheres, boxes, cylinders, etc.) and defines how they are modified and combined (for instance by intersection, difference, envelope combination and [[Minkowski sum]]s) to render a [[3D model]]. As such, the program does [[constructive solid geometry]] (CSG). OpenSCAD is available for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[Linux]] and [[OS X]].\n\n== Previewing ==\nFor fast previewing of models using [[z-buffering]], OpenSCAD employs [[OpenCSG]] and [[OpenGL]].\n\nThe 3D model position can be interactively manipulated in the view with a mouse similarly to other 3D modellers. It is also possible to define a default \"camera\" position in the script.\n\nPart colors can be defined in the 3D view (including transparency).<ref>Transparency is evaluated in the construction order, so a part is only transparent for parts already built.</ref>\n\nPreview is relatively fast and allows interactive modifications while modifying the script.\n\nThe model renderer takes into account lighting, but the lighting source is not modifiable.\n\n== Use ==\nOpenSCAD allows a designer to create accurate 3D models and [[solid modeling#Parametric modeling|parametric designs]] that can be easily adjusted by changing the parameters.<ref>{{citation |first=Brian |last=Evans |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FPSsCTE9KpgC |title=Practical 3D Printers: The Science and Art of 3D Printing |year=2012 |page=113 |publisher=Apress |isbn=9781430243922 }}.</ref>\n\nOpenSCAD documents are human-readable scripts in plain ASCII text.\n\nAs such, OpenSCAD is a programmer-oriented solid-modeling tool<ref>{{citation |first1=Bre |last1=Pettis |first2=Anna Kaziunas |last2=France |first3=Jay |last3=Shergill |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-iaTMXZJQ9cC |title=Getting Started with MakerBot |publisher=O'Reilly Media, Inc. |year=2012 |page=131 |isbn=9781449338657}}.</ref> and has been recommended as an entry-level [[Computer-aided design|CAD]] tool for designing [[open-source hardware]] such as scientific tools for research and education.<ref>{{citation |first=Joshua M. |last=Pearce |authorlink=Joshua Pearce |title=Open-Source Lab: How to Build Your Own Hardware and Reduce Research Costs |publisher=Elsevier |year=2014 |isbn=9780124104624 |chapter=Chapter 6: \u201eDigital Designs and Scientific Hardware\u201c|pages=165\u2013254|title-link=Open-Source Lab (book) }}.</ref>\n\nIt is mostly used to design [[3D printing|3D printed]] parts, which are exported in [[STL (file format)|STL]] format.\n\n[[File:Strandbeest 3d - crank offset corrected.gif|thumb|Animation created with OpenSCAD]]\nAnimation is possible with a speed of a few images per seconds for simple models. The animation can have effect on any parameter, being it the camera position or the parts dimensions, position, shape or existence.\nIt can be recorded as a set of images usable to build films.\n\n== Exportation ==\n* Views can be exported in [[Portable Network Graphics|PNG]] format.\n* 2D models can be exported in [[AutoCAD DXF]].\n* 3D parts can be exported in [[Additive Manufacturing File Format|AMF]], [[OFF (file format)|OFF]], [[STL (file format)|STL]], as simple volumes. There is no color, material nor parts definition in the exported model (July 2016).\n\n== Importation ==\n* 2D drawings in DXF,SVG and PNG can be imported, then extruded as monolithic parts.\n* 3D parts can be imported in STL and can be scaled and submitted to subtractive or additive operations.\n\n== Design ==\nOpenScad is a wrapper to a [[Constructive_solid_geometry|CSG]] engine with a graphical user interface and integrated editor, developed in C++. As of 2016, it uses the [[Computational Geometry Algorithms Library]] (CGAL) as its basic CSG engine.\n\nIts script syntax reflects a [[functional programming]] philosophy. Much as in [[Haskell (programming language)|Haskell]], within a scope each \"variable\" is treated as a constant, immutable with at most one value.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n\n* [[List of computer-aided design editors for architecture, engineering and construction]]\n* [[PLaSM]] is another open source scripting language for creating 3D objects\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{wikibooks-inline|OpenSCAD User Manual}}\n* [http://www.shapeoko.com/wiki/index.php/OpenSCAD OpenSCAD page on Shapeoko wiki] \u2014 includes links to supporting utilities, special purpose tools (such as a screw generator) and includes an example of creating a Machinist's diamond, circle, square milling test as a parameterized file suitable for re-creating at any desired size.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n0HMJ_OfzYE&list=PLXFMUfzq5U4QvHGHRwuSr4KmzZBiqW1iP Videos on the basics of modeling with OpenSCAD]\n\n=== Related software ===\n*[http://openjscad.org/  OpenJscad] Web interface for a programmatic modeller with partial compatibility with OpenScad scripts. Developed in Javascript.